{"id": "food_FOOD00058", "name": "Coffee (food medium)", "category": "food", "organism_scope": "food microbiome / general", "aerobic": true, "description": "Food-derived medium: metabolizable components of Coffee (Coffea) [Coffee and coffee products] from FooDB, plus a standard M9 mineral base. Organic components use presence-based uptake bounds; FooDB content retained. Measured compounds with no BiGG exchange are listed under uncovered.", "namespace": "bigg", "provenance": {"source_type": "database", "citation": "FooDB v2020-04-07 (Wishart DS et al., foodb.ca). Content sources: DTU, PHENOL EXPLORER, USDA.", "doi": "", "url": "https://foodb.ca/downloads", "notes": "Organic components mapped from FooDB compounds to BiGG via InChIKey/name. Mineral base added. Bounds presence-based; foodb_content retained. Unmapped measured compounds kept in uncovered (v2 completeness fix). IMPORTANT: composition values are taken from the archived FooDB 2020-04-07 CSV data release; FooDB's live food page no longer displays this bulk composition, so it will appear empty. Verify individual compounds via the per-component cross-reference links. Underlying content was aggregated by FooDB from USDA / DTU / Phenol Explorer.", "data_release": "FooDB 2020-04-07 CSV release (foodb.ca/downloads)", "food_record": "https://foodb.ca/foods/FOOD00058", "verification": "expert-curated (multi-source food composition; growth-relevant profile completed, FooDB noise removed)", "curation_date": "2026-07-17", "curation_sources": ["USDA FoodData Central / SR Legacy NDB 14209 'Coffee, brewed from grounds, prepared with tap water'", "Rune, Giacalone, Steen et al. 2023, Current Research in Food Science 6:100485, doi:10.1016/j.crfs.2023.100485 (individual organic acids & sugars in French-press brewed coffee)", "Konieczka et al. 2020, LWT (S0023643820303339) and Wu et al. 2023 (trigonelline in coffee brews)", "FooDB FOOD00058 (Coffee)"], "curation_notes": "For a growth medium, brewed coffee is a dilute (~99% water), nitrogen-poor beverage whose dominant carbon/energy substrates are ORGANIC ACIDS — chlorogenic and quinic acids first, then acetic, citric, formic, lactic, malic — with only modest free glucose/fructose that survive roasting (light roasts only). Caffeine (~40 mg/100 mL) and trigonelline (~50 mg/100 mL) are abundant but largely non-nutritive/inhibitory. Potassium is the main mineral. Acid/sugar amounts come from a specialty French-press", "curation_added": ["chlorogenic acid", "quinic acid", "citric acid", "acetic acid", "phosphoric acid", "lactic acid", "formic acid", "malic acid", "glycolic acid", "D-glucose (with amount)", "D-fructose (with amount)", "caffeine (with amount)", "trigonelline (with amount)"], "curation_removed": [{"name": "Cholesterol", "reason": "Animal sterol; biologically implausible in a plant-derived beverage; FooDB predicted, not measured."}, {"name": "Retinol", "reason": "Preformed (animal-form) vitamin A; USDA reports 0 in brewed coffee; implausible in a plant beverage."}, {"name": "Beta-Carotene", "reason": "USDA reports negligible/zero provitamin A carotenoid in brewed coffee; FooDB predicted."}, {"name": "Cyanocobalamin", "reason": "Vitamin B12 is not synthesised by plants; not present in coffee; FooDB predicted/implausible."}, {"name": "Phytomenadione", "reason": "Vitamin K1; USDA reports 0 in brewed coffee; negligible in the brew."}, {"name": "L-Ascorbate", "reason": "Vitamin C; USDA reports 0 in brewed coffee; heat/roast-labile and absent from the beverage."}, {"name": "Starch C12H20O10", "reason": "No starch is extracted into the brewed beverage (retained in the grounds); USDA carbohydrate ~0."}, {"name": "Nickel", "reason": "Ultratrace, non-nutritive in this matrix; FooDB contaminant-level entry, not a growth nutrient."}, {"name": "Co2+", "reason": "Cobalt ion at ultratrace/contaminant level; not a defined growth nutrient of the brew."}, {"name": "Decanoic acid / Dodecanoic acid / Pentadecanoic acid / Octanoic acid / Heptanoate / 